  <exercise label="Superposition Z">
    <title>
      <c>Z</c> Gate Behavior with Superposition
    </title>
    <idx>superpositionZ</idx>
    <statement>
      <p>What is the effect of the sequence <c>H</c>-<c>Z</c>-<c>H</c> on qubits beginning in <m>\ket{0}</m> or <m>
          \ket{1}
        </m>?</p>
      <image source="Checkpoint3.2-Z-gate-behavior-with-Superposition.png" width="66%" />
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice correct="no">
        <statement>
          <p>equal chance of measuring 0 or 1.</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p> </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>No observable effect. </p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p> </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement>
          <p>The same as a <c>NOT</c> gate</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Correct!</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
    <hint>
      <p>Think about what the output would be after each gate.</p>
    </hint>
  </exercise>
  <p>
    Now we see that <c>Z</c> does have a major effect on the system, but <em>only</em> when the
    qubit is in superposition.
  </p>
  <p>
    We need a mathematical representation of phase that will allow us to perform operations
    to calculate results. We will express phase as positive (+) or negative (-).
    Starting with a qubit in the <m>\ket{0}</m> state results in positive (+) phase, and
    starting in <m>\ket{1}</m> state results in negative (-) phase.
  </p>
  <p>
    Likewise, if the qubit is already in the superposition 50/50 state, if it is in positive phase,
    applying an <c>H</c> gate will result in <m>\ket{0}</m>. An <c>H</c> gate applied to a qubit in the
    superposition 50/50 state in negative phase will result in <m>\ket{1}</m>.
    The truth table for the <c>Z</c> gate is below. I suggest adding this to your page of notes.
  </p>
